 played an increasingly important role. As the reform movement spread beyond the government apparatus, emerging groups of officers, bureaucrats, and urban professionals incorporated novel time-related ideas, values, and behaviors into their self-consciously “modern” outlook and lifestyle. Acculturated in the highly regimented environment of schools and barracks, they came to identify efficiency and temporal regularity with progress and the former temporal patterns with the old political order. Drawing on a wealth of archival and literary sources, Wishnitzer’s original and highly important work presents the shifting culture of time as an arena in which Ottoman social groups competed for legitimacy and a medium through which the very concept of modernity was defined. Reading Clocks, Alla Turca breaks new ground in the study of the Middle East and presents us with a new understanding of the relationship between time and modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aTimexSocial aspectszTurkey. 0aTimexSystems and standardszTurkeyxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  atime, ottoman empire, clocks, temporal culture, assimilation, economy, trade, commerce, state building, surveillance, regularity, efficiency, reform, social change, bureaucracy, schools, barracks, military, progress, modernity, legitimacy, authority, turkey, clerk, labor, employment, transportation, perception, technology, schedule, sociology, anthropology, history, political cartoons, police reports, ferry schedules, timetables, erotic poetry, nonfiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022625772340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226257860423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226257860/original  a978-3-11-069043-9